author: {'id': 3244031}
body:
Waterbury’s Palace Theater hosted its annual Martinis & Mistletoe holiday party and fundraiser sponsored by Tito’s Handmade Vodka and Ion Bank on Dec. 7. The event showcased festive holiday cocktails by six local venues: Diorio Restaurant & Bar, Jesse Camille’s Restaurant, The Kitchen in Prospect Bar & Grill, Sans Souci Restaurant, Signatures Restaurant and Vyne Restaurant & Bar. More than 200 guests attended the holiday event, which showcased bartenders from each venue, who were on-site mixing and pouring craft cocktails for guests using Tito’s Handmade Vodka as the base spirit. Guests were invited to vote for their favorite, ultimately choosing the Blue Christmas cocktail by Sans Souci Restaurant by Chloe Tompkins and Polly Zagorski as the winner. Guests also enjoyed light fare by Emily’s Catering, a photo station, a raffle drawing and live music by Marty Q throughout the evening. All proceeds benefited the Palace Theater Annual Fund, which is used to preserve and operate the historic theater and continue to serve diverse audiences with its cultural and educational offerings.
Waterbury’s Palace Theater hosted its annual Martinis & Mistletoe holiday party and fundraiser sponsored by Tito’s Handmade Vodka on Dec. 7.
 John and Cathy Testa, Diorio Restaurant & Bar with their cocktail, Sex on a Snowbank Winter.
 A pour of the Sugarplumtini by Joe Laliberte and Kelsie Gorman, Signatures Restaurant.
 Vyne Restaurant & Bar’s Fig Tree Martini.
 Photos 1, 2, 4 and 6-10 courtesy of Felix Manuel Photography.
 Photos 3 and 5 by Andrea Madrid.

author: {'id': 3064111}
body:
Police are investigating after two people allegedly shot at a driver during an attempted robbery at a bank in Meriden on Sunday.
 Authorities said they were called to ION Bank on West Main Street at 10:25 p.m. for the attempted armed robbery.
  A person reported that two individuals with guns tried to rob them while using the drive-up ATM. A car pulled up beside the victim's vehicle and when they tried to flee, the suspects fired gunshots at the vehicle, according to police.
  No one was hurt during the incident. Police are actively investigating and anyone with information is asked to contact Detective Pellegrini at 203-630-6297 or bpellegrini@meridenct.gov
  The police department is reminding folks to take measures to protect their ATM card, including keeping the card in a safe place and keeping your PIN number a secret.
  When using an ATM, police say you should be aware of your surroundings, particularly at night. If you see anything suspicious, do not use the machine and report it. More tips are available on the police department's Facebook page

author: {'id': 1065025500}
body:
We’ve opened our newest branch at 376 N. Main Street in Southington. This 22nd branch is a milestone for us with our first EV charging station which can charge two vehicles simultaneously. While offering added convenience to customers, we are thrilled to do our part by reducing our carbon footprint to help improve air quality and lower greenhouse gas emissions.

Along with our friendly personalized service in the branch, we are happy to serve you with our Personal Teller Machine (PTM) technology. Our PTMs allow for face-to-face banking via video with extended hours from 7am – 8pm Monday through Friday and 7am – 3pm on Saturday. This PTM technology allows you to interact with a live teller through two-way video for typical transactions such as making deposits and payments, withdrawals, transferring money, cashing checks, and more.

In addition to building lifetime relationships by partnering with you to help identify and achieve your financial goals, our family partner Ion Investments offers wealth management and life insurance products for a healthy financial future.



We’re so happy to be able to bring our friendly personalized banking, wealth management, insurance services, and values to the Southington community.

title: Ion Bank is Now in Southington

author: {'id': 100282}
body:
Naugatuck-based Ion Bank recently announced a new hire and a promotion.

Diane M. Dornfried has been hired as a vice president, mortgage originator. Dornfried will primarily support the Meriden and Southington markets, assisting customers looking to purchase, refinance or get a home equity line of credit. She most recently was a mortgage originator for Collinsville Bank.

Image Diane M. Dornfried

Kalim Jan has been promoted to senior vice president, treasurer. Jan will be responsible for investment portfolio management, interest rate risk analysis and will serve as a member of the asset liability committee.



Jan has been employed at Ion Financial since 2013, starting as a credit analyst and then taking on higher positions within the company.

title: Ion Bank announces new hire and promotion

author: {'id': 3044189, 'name': 'Nj Staff'}
body:
Ion Bank announced two new members have joined its commercial lending team: Alfred Nunan and Christina Good.
Nunan joins the Montville-based financial institution as a senior vice president, New Jersey Commercial Banking Team leader, and Good is a senior vice president, commercial lender. Nunan and Good will work closely with local businesses to develop and expand commercial relationships for new and existing customers. They will be trusted advisers and partner with businesses to help them grow their business.
 In his new role, Nunan will support and develop his staff, in addition to serving his community. In the role of senior vice president, commercial lender, Good will source new lending opportunities with a dedicated focus on commercial real estate, provide customized solutions and develop lifetime relationships.
 “The combined experience of Alfred and Christina of over 50 years will enable them to provide the knowledge and expertise to effectively develop and expand commercial relationships for new and existing customers while providing the level of personalized service necessary to achieve their financial goals,” Jayne Kelly, executive vice president, chief commercial banking officer, said.
 Nunan was previously an SVP, middle market banking, at Wells Fargo Bank in Summit. He received a Bachelor of Science in business administration/economics from Monmouth University. He is a current board member of the Greater Morristown YMCA and the Irish American Cultural Institute, past president of the Irish Business Association of New Jersey, and past trustee of Trinitas Health Foundation.

', 'Nunan and Good will work closely with local businesses to develop and expand commercial relationships for new and existing customers.', 'In the role of senior vice president, commercial lender, Good will source new lending opportunities with a dedicated focus on commercial real estate, provide customized solutions and develop lifetime relationships.
 ', 'Nunan joins the Montville-based financial institution as a senior vice president, New Jersey Commercial Banking Team leader, and Good is a senior vice president, commercial lender.', '“The combined experience of Alfred and Christina of over 50 years will enable them to provide the knowledge and expertise to effectively develop and expand commercial relationships for new and existing customers while providing the level of personalized service necessary to achieve their financial goals,” Jayne Kelly, executive vice president, chief commercial banking officer, said.

body:
From left: Cara Luciani (President Cheshire Lions Club); Bill Manthey (Treasurer of Cheshire Road Races); Craig Porter (Ion Bank Director of Marketing and Communications and VP of Cheshire Road Races); Llyod Saberski, MD (Cheshire Road Races President); Lezlye Zupkus (Best Buddies CT State Director). Photo by Tony Cipriano
The 2023 Ion Bank Cheshire Road Races donated more than $60,000 to local charities! At a recent check presentation ceremony, one $62,000 check was presented to the event’s three principle charitable partners: Abilities Without Boundaries, Best Buddies CT, and the Cheshire Lions Club. These donations would not be possible without the generous support of sponsors and participants.
 The 11th annual event, held on April 23, attracted a crowd of over 1,500 participants. Since the inaugural year in 2012, the Ion Bank Cheshire Road Race’s charitable focus has been on raising money and awareness for local organizations that support individuals with special needs. Volunteers from the event’s signature charities donate their time and efforts as board members, as well as helping out during race weekend. The support of these volunteers continues to make the Ion Bank Cheshire Road Races an annual success!
 Cheshire Half Marathon & 5K Race President, Lloyd Saberski, was happy with this year’s contributions. Saberski stated, “With the help of our sponsors and participants, we were able to continue to donate to these charities every year. The race committee is very pleased with the results of this year’s race and we look forward to increasing charitable contributions and adding additional beneficiaries in the years to come.”
 Major sponsors of the event include Ion Bank, Audi of Wallingford, Porsche of Wallingford, Yale New Haven Health, and Connecticut Orthopaedic Specialists.
 The Ion Bank Cheshire Road Race is organized by the Cheshire Half Marathon Foundation Board of Directors. The board is comprised of nearly 20 members with diverse backgrounds from the Cheshire community. Along with the race committee, JB Sports, coordinator of the MJP Wealth Advisors Fairfield Road Races and the Faxon Law New Haven Road Races, is organizing the event.
 To register or learn more, visit cheshirehalfmarathon.org or call (203) 481-5933.

title: Ion Bank Road Races donates $62K

author: {'id': 1002951999}
body:
Photo courtesy of Allen Dvarskas - Ion Bank Cheshire Road Races donated $60,000 to local charities in 2023. A recent check presentation was held at Cheshire High School to make the announcement.
The 2023 Ion Bank Cheshire Road Races donated nearly $60,000 to local charities. At a recent check presentation, a $10,000 check was presented to Cheshire High School.
 The 11th annual event, held on April 23, attracted a crowd of over 1,500 participants. Since the inaugural year in 2012, the Ion Bank Cheshire Road Race’s charitable focus has been on raising money and awareness for local organizations that support individuals with special needs. Volunteers from the event’s signature charities donate their time and efforts as board members, as well as helping out during race weekend. The support of these volunteers continues to make the Ion Bank Cheshire Road Races an annual success.
 Cheshire Half Marathon & 5K Race President, Lloyd Saberski, was happy with this year’s contributions. Saberski stated, “With the help of our sponsors and participants, we were able to continue to donate to these charities every year. The race committee is very pleased with the results of this year’s race and we look forward to increasing charitable contributions and adding additional beneficiaries in the years to come.”
 Major sponsors of the event include Ion Bank, Audi of Wallingford, Porsche of Wallingford, Yale New Haven Health, and Connecticut Orthopaedic Specialists.
 The Ion Bank Cheshire Road Race is organized by the Cheshire Half Marathon Foundation Board of Directors. The board is comprised of nearly 20 members with diverse backgrounds from the Cheshire community. Along with the race committee, JB Sports, coordinator of the MJP Wealth Advisors Fairfield Road Races and the Faxon Law New Haven Road Races, is organizing the event.
